WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.875
- Your guys'-

00:00:00.875 --> 00:00:01.876
- Oh my god.
- chemistry was amazing,

00:00:01.876 --> 00:00:03.545
have you ever kissed?

00:00:03.545 --> 00:00:05.714
- I got a Matchbox car commercial

00:00:05.714 --> 00:00:07.590
where I played a gangster.

00:00:07.590 --> 00:00:10.260
- Why did somebody dose everyone

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:12.595
and why would they waste drugs?

00:00:12.595 --> 00:00:15.098
(jazz music)

00:00:24.065 --> 00:00:24.941
- You're starting?

00:00:24.941 --> 00:00:26.901
- Yeah, I'd like to start.
- Okay.

00:00:26.901 --> 00:00:27.986
- Because "One Battle After Another"

00:00:27.986 --> 00:00:29.738
is my favorite movie I've ever seen

00:00:29.738 --> 00:00:31.698
in my life.
- Oh, Thank you. Oh, stop.

00:00:31.698 --> 00:00:32.615
- No, really...

00:00:33.658 --> 00:00:36.536
You're a really, really,
really great actor,

00:00:36.536 --> 00:00:39.289
and this was like the greatest
performance I've ever seen.

00:00:39.289 --> 00:00:40.123
- Stop.

00:00:40.123 --> 00:00:41.624
- And what struck me just as somebody,

00:00:41.624 --> 00:00:46.629
'cause I know you and I
thought this character was so,

00:00:46.713 --> 00:00:48.506
it was like the rawest I've ever seen you,

00:00:48.506 --> 00:00:50.842
but you were also really warm.

00:00:50.842 --> 00:00:55.722
And Bob reminded me,
not in like personality,

00:00:55.722 --> 00:01:00.727
but I guess in like values of your dad.

00:01:01.019 --> 00:01:04.355
And I know your parents were
like very counterculture.

00:01:04.355 --> 00:01:05.690
- Yeah.
- So was there something

00:01:05.690 --> 00:01:08.777
that was like built from you about Bob

00:01:08.777 --> 00:01:10.528
or like do you think PTA just kind of

00:01:10.528 --> 00:01:13.823
handed you a really warm and amazing guy?

00:01:13.823 --> 00:01:17.452
- I think it was very personal for Paul.

00:01:17.452 --> 00:01:20.371
He'd been writing it for 15, 20 years

00:01:20.371 --> 00:01:22.373
and it was very pertinent to today,

00:01:22.373 --> 00:01:23.666
very topical.
- Yeah.

00:01:24.834 --> 00:01:26.336
- But yeah, it was, you know,

00:01:26.336 --> 00:01:29.380
it was based on violent

00:01:29.380 --> 00:01:32.175
but he made his own
rendition of all of it.

00:01:32.175 --> 00:01:34.886
And I think the idea of this guy

00:01:34.886 --> 00:01:36.304
who was a revolutionary

00:01:36.304 --> 00:01:40.141
then trying to assimilate
himself in the modern world

00:01:40.141 --> 00:01:42.435
with a daughter that he didn't connect to

00:01:43.311 --> 00:01:45.605
was something that had
been permeating in his mind

00:01:45.605 --> 00:01:46.940
for a long time, but as far as like

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:48.691
the counterculture stuff, yeah, my,

00:01:49.734 --> 00:01:51.277
my parents are different though.

00:01:51.277 --> 00:01:53.530
You know, my dad hung
around with Abby Hoffman

00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:55.740
a bit back in the day.

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:56.908
They were definitely hippies,

00:01:56.908 --> 00:01:59.244
but these were much more hardcore

00:01:59.244 --> 00:02:00.995
revolutionaries that did-
- Oh yeah.

00:02:00.995 --> 00:02:02.997
(Leonardo and Jennifer laughing)

00:02:02.997 --> 00:02:04.582
- Much crazier stuff.

00:02:04.582 --> 00:02:06.042
But yeah.
- Your dad was also

00:02:06.042 --> 00:02:07.252
a bomb maker.

00:02:07.252 --> 00:02:09.504
- My father was a bomb maker.
- Yeah.

00:02:09.504 --> 00:02:11.840
- But I dunno, I just love the idea of

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:12.799
picking up on this guy

00:02:12.799 --> 00:02:15.218
who was just kind of essentially an extra

00:02:15.218 --> 00:02:17.095
in the beginning of the movie

00:02:17.095 --> 00:02:20.807
to Teyana's sort of revolutionary fire.

00:02:20.807 --> 00:02:22.392
And then you find him stuck there

00:02:22.392 --> 00:02:26.062
trying to live off the grid
with no internet, no phone,

00:02:26.062 --> 00:02:28.731
thinking his daughter's gonna
be as paranoid as he is.

00:02:28.731 --> 00:02:32.318
And then this idea of
them trying to reconnect

00:02:32.318 --> 00:02:33.528
in a modern context

00:02:33.528 --> 00:02:35.446
and he doesn't even know how
to relate to his daughter

00:02:35.446 --> 00:02:37.407
or the world that he lives in.

00:02:37.407 --> 00:02:38.658
But all that was in the script

00:02:38.658 --> 00:02:40.952
and something that Paul, you know,

00:02:40.952 --> 00:02:42.954
put a lot of thought into.

00:02:42.954 --> 00:02:44.706
- [Phone Recipient] What time is it?

00:02:47.041 --> 00:02:48.710
- You know, I don't, I don't,
I don't remember that part.

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:51.462
Or let, let, let's just not
nitpick over the password stuff.

00:02:51.462 --> 00:02:53.965
- It was the funniest I've ever seen you.

00:02:53.965 --> 00:02:55.508
And was that because you were
- Thank you.

00:02:55.508 --> 00:02:58.052
- were you like aware of the comedy?

00:02:58.052 --> 00:02:59.637
'cause I think the funniest people

00:02:59.637 --> 00:03:00.972
are like an Alec Baldwin

00:03:00.972 --> 00:03:03.683
who like does it like as
serious as a heart attack,

00:03:03.683 --> 00:03:04.684
and I can't do that.

00:03:04.684 --> 00:03:06.269
Like when I was doing "No Hard Feelings,"

00:03:06.269 --> 00:03:08.605
I was too like aware that it was a joke

00:03:08.605 --> 00:03:10.732
and I was like, yay, a joke's coming up,

00:03:10.732 --> 00:03:11.566
and I don't think-
- Right.

00:03:11.566 --> 00:03:12.400
- I could do that.

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:14.986
But did you, were you like
aware that you were being funny

00:03:14.986 --> 00:03:16.613
or were you just really-

00:03:16.613 --> 00:03:17.947
- It was the circumstances.

00:03:17.947 --> 00:03:20.450
I mean the fact that Paul wrote this idea

00:03:20.450 --> 00:03:22.702
that you think I'm
gonna be able to utilize

00:03:22.702 --> 00:03:25.872
all the skills from my
past as a revolutionary,

00:03:25.872 --> 00:03:28.249
but that he's too stoned
to get off the couch

00:03:28.249 --> 00:03:30.001
and he can't remember the password,

00:03:30.001 --> 00:03:33.046
and then that kind of
dominates the entire story.

00:03:33.046 --> 00:03:33.880
- Right.

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:36.341
- And then each time
we got to these moments

00:03:36.341 --> 00:03:39.177
or maybe my character was
gonna do something heroic,

00:03:39.177 --> 00:03:40.345
we throw it out the window,

00:03:40.345 --> 00:03:41.471
all the way to the end.

00:03:41.471 --> 00:03:43.556
- Yeah. When you fell off the roof.

00:03:43.556 --> 00:03:45.725
- All the way to the
final moment in the movie

00:03:45.725 --> 00:03:46.643
where we still thought

00:03:46.643 --> 00:03:48.353
maybe I was gonna do something heroic,

00:03:48.353 --> 00:03:52.273
we're like, nah, nah, he doesn't do it.

00:03:52.273 --> 00:03:56.611
- Yeah, Benicio also never
really got his moment of

00:03:56.611 --> 00:03:59.906
like all this kind of work,

00:03:59.906 --> 00:04:01.157
and then there wasn't like a moment

00:04:01.157 --> 00:04:02.617
where he rides off into the sunset.

00:04:02.617 --> 00:04:04.827
- Right.
- It was just kind of-

00:04:04.827 --> 00:04:05.954
- He was fantastic

00:04:05.954 --> 00:04:06.788
to work with.
- He was.

00:04:06.788 --> 00:04:07.622
Your guys'-

00:04:07.622 --> 00:04:08.456
- Oh, my god-
- chemistry was amazing,

00:04:08.456 --> 00:04:09.707
have you ever kissed?

00:04:09.707 --> 00:04:11.918
(Leonardo and Jennifer laughing)

00:04:11.918 --> 00:04:14.170
- The heat was actually
doing "Phoenicin Scheme"

00:04:14.170 --> 00:04:15.755
and we said we have to wait for him.

00:04:15.755 --> 00:04:18.508
So we shut down production
for three months

00:04:18.508 --> 00:04:20.802
and then he was like, "I'm not,
I'm not prepared for this."

00:04:20.802 --> 00:04:23.888
But he came in and knew
exactly who his character was

00:04:23.888 --> 00:04:26.432
and we changed the whole
movie when he arrived.

00:04:26.432 --> 00:04:27.267
- Yeah.

00:04:27.267 --> 00:04:29.185
- All stuff we did on the road

00:04:29.185 --> 00:04:31.271
is because Benicio was like,
"No, I'm not doing this,

00:04:31.271 --> 00:04:32.897
I am doing this, this is hu Sensei,

00:04:32.897 --> 00:04:33.898
no, this is what he's..."

00:04:33.898 --> 00:04:35.608
and we just kind of made up,

00:04:35.608 --> 00:04:39.028
we improvised most of that stuff

00:04:39.028 --> 00:04:41.197
that we did together.
- Wow.

00:04:41.197 --> 00:04:44.617
- This is at the end of the line, huh?

00:04:44.617 --> 00:04:47.328
- Not for you.

00:04:47.328 --> 00:04:49.414
Ocean waves, ocean waves.

00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:51.624
- Well, one last question.
- Okay.

00:04:51.624 --> 00:04:54.377
- I have more, but
before we move on to me,

00:04:54.377 --> 00:04:56.170
do you watch playback?

00:04:56.170 --> 00:04:57.588
- Depends on the movie.

00:04:57.588 --> 00:04:58.881
- Did you watch playback on this?

00:04:58.881 --> 00:05:00.049
- No.
- Oh yeah, you couldn't

00:05:00.049 --> 00:05:01.759
because of the film.
- It was all VistaVision.

00:05:01.759 --> 00:05:02.593
- Right.

00:05:02.593 --> 00:05:05.179
- Almost endangered or extinct cameras.

00:05:05.179 --> 00:05:06.931
- Giovanni Ribisi.
- Yes.

00:05:06.931 --> 00:05:07.974
- [Jennifer] Yeah.

00:05:07.974 --> 00:05:11.102
- I actually told Paul about
Giovanni Ribisi who makes

00:05:11.102 --> 00:05:12.437
a lot of these cameras.
- Yeah.

00:05:12.437 --> 00:05:15.273
- A lot of them are from Hitchcock's era.

00:05:15.273 --> 00:05:17.567
The last film was "One-Eyed Jacks."

00:05:17.567 --> 00:05:20.695
And then "The Brutalist" shot
something in VistaVision.

00:05:20.695 --> 00:05:22.155
But the thing about VistaVision cameras,

00:05:22.155 --> 00:05:24.073
not only are there incredibly rare

00:05:24.073 --> 00:05:25.867
and that's when Giovanni
stepped in and said,

00:05:25.867 --> 00:05:28.995
"Hey, I have two of these
cameras that I put together,"

00:05:30.747 --> 00:05:33.708
the projectors, there's
only like four in the world.

00:05:33.708 --> 00:05:35.251
- Wow.
- The film goes this way

00:05:35.251 --> 00:05:39.422
and it's very, you know, I
think Cinemascope took it over,

00:05:39.422 --> 00:05:42.216
but now there was, so it was no playback.

00:05:42.216 --> 00:05:43.051
- Yeah.

00:05:43.885 --> 00:05:45.094
A lot of rollouts.

00:05:45.094 --> 00:05:46.971
- A lot of rollouts.

00:05:46.971 --> 00:05:50.641
And we actually, I think
only destroyed one camera.

00:05:50.641 --> 00:05:51.809
- Destroyed it how?

00:05:51.809 --> 00:05:53.102
- Yeah.

00:05:53.102 --> 00:05:56.522
Driving, the driving trucks.
- Oh man.

00:05:56.522 --> 00:05:57.899
I saw the movie on IMAX

00:05:57.899 --> 00:05:58.733
and those driving scenes

00:05:58.733 --> 00:06:00.401
were amazing.
- Oh, really?

00:06:00.401 --> 00:06:03.112
- Like stomach dropping, so good.

00:06:03.112 --> 00:06:04.864
- So do you think you'll have another one?

00:06:04.864 --> 00:06:06.532
- Yeah, pregnant now.

00:06:06.532 --> 00:06:07.450
Picking up twins.

00:06:08.576 --> 00:06:10.244
- What happened to your hands?

00:06:10.244 --> 00:06:13.247
- Oh, you should see the wall.

00:06:13.247 --> 00:06:14.582
- So tell me about "Die My Love,"

00:06:14.582 --> 00:06:17.710
I thought it was, I just
finished it this morning

00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:20.963
because this all got decided yesterday.

00:06:20.963 --> 00:06:24.300
But it kind of reminded
me of like French New Wave

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:26.552
or Cassavetes's filmmaking

00:06:26.552 --> 00:06:29.931
and I thought immediately of
"Woman Under the Influence,"

00:06:29.931 --> 00:06:32.100
which is one of my favorite performances.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:32.934
- Me too.
- And one of MY

00:06:32.934 --> 00:06:34.310
favorite movies.
- Yeah.

00:06:34.310 --> 00:06:37.688
- So why did you wanna do this part?

00:06:37.688 --> 00:06:39.107
What got you into it?

00:06:39.107 --> 00:06:41.484
You were fantastic in it, tell me more.

00:06:41.484 --> 00:06:42.318
- Thanks.

00:06:42.318 --> 00:06:44.362
Martin Scorsese had read the book-

00:06:44.362 --> 00:06:45.530
- That's right
- in his book club,

00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:48.116
and he was like, "You
should be in this movie

00:06:48.116 --> 00:06:51.035
or you should make this into
a movie and star in it."

00:06:51.035 --> 00:06:53.037
And then when I was reading it,

00:06:53.037 --> 00:06:56.290
I really couldn't understand
how it would be a movie

00:06:56.290 --> 00:06:58.876
'cause it's like all her inner dialogue.

00:06:59.752 --> 00:07:01.379
I got the emotion of it,

00:07:01.379 --> 00:07:03.965
like I felt like the author Ariana Harwicz

00:07:03.965 --> 00:07:07.427
was able to like describe
the indescribable,

00:07:07.427 --> 00:07:12.432
like grave depression and
like an identity crisis,

00:07:13.433 --> 00:07:17.103
but like really poetically
like being lost in a forest

00:07:17.103 --> 00:07:18.438
and just like these visuals-
- Yeah.

00:07:18.438 --> 00:07:19.272
- and these metaphors

00:07:19.272 --> 00:07:21.482
that I had just never thought of like

00:07:21.482 --> 00:07:23.943
the human condition in that way.

00:07:23.943 --> 00:07:26.487
But I couldn't like crack
how to make it a movie,

00:07:26.487 --> 00:07:27.864
and I didn't wanna like go back to Marty

00:07:27.864 --> 00:07:30.408
and be like, I don't get
it, try someone else.

00:07:30.408 --> 00:07:31.492
So I like-
- The ending is really

00:07:31.492 --> 00:07:32.910
powerful.
- Well it's interesting

00:07:32.910 --> 00:07:37.290
because it, okay, so once I
realized that it's poetry,

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:40.626
you know, it's not like a literal story,

00:07:40.626 --> 00:07:44.630
then it clicked that it's Lynne
Ramsay 'cause she's a poet.

00:07:44.630 --> 00:07:46.174
- And what stuff was in the book?

00:07:46.174 --> 00:07:49.594
Was there stuff in the book
that wasn't in the movie?

00:07:49.594 --> 00:07:51.512
Or is it pretty much-

00:07:51.512 --> 00:07:52.805
- No, she changed a lot.

00:07:52.805 --> 00:07:54.182
- She changed a lot.
- She made the couple

00:07:54.182 --> 00:07:57.393
be new to town, which
in the book they're not,

00:07:57.393 --> 00:08:01.522
and I think that adds a huge element

00:08:01.522 --> 00:08:04.567
to my characters depression.

00:08:04.567 --> 00:08:09.572
And I think also the kind of
pacing like a tiger in a cage,

00:08:09.614 --> 00:08:11.157
you know, just like this,

00:08:11.157 --> 00:08:15.578
I think it added a lot more
of like the isolation that

00:08:15.578 --> 00:08:18.873
I think a lot of new parents have.

00:08:18.873 --> 00:08:21.751
'Cause like what is my life
now without a community?

00:08:21.751 --> 00:08:23.127
- Right.
- Just being really lost.

00:08:23.127 --> 00:08:24.337
At the beginning,

00:08:24.337 --> 00:08:26.839
both of our characters kind
of stick out like sore thumbs.

00:08:26.839 --> 00:08:27.673
- Yeah.

00:08:27.673 --> 00:08:28.883
- 'cause we're like from a big city

00:08:28.883 --> 00:08:30.593
and we're in this small town,

00:08:30.593 --> 00:08:33.262
and then as the movie progresses,

00:08:33.262 --> 00:08:35.389
I start to like blend in

00:08:35.389 --> 00:08:38.851
and then that was my way of like finding

00:08:38.851 --> 00:08:40.478
where I was in the day.

00:08:40.478 --> 00:08:44.190
Like where she was mentally.

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:45.691
Like I'd be like, oh, the pink cardigan,

00:08:45.691 --> 00:08:47.985
okay she's (tongue clicking).

00:08:47.985 --> 00:08:51.572
- For a lot of the tension
for me was that baby.

00:08:51.572 --> 00:08:52.365
- [Jennifer] Yeah.

00:08:52.365 --> 00:08:53.324
- You know-
- I know

00:08:53.324 --> 00:08:55.117
- You think of the tension
in a film like this,

00:08:55.117 --> 00:08:58.037
you're like, okay, what's
gonna happen to this child?

00:08:58.037 --> 00:08:58.871
- I know.

00:08:58.871 --> 00:09:01.707
- Because she's unraveled.
- Yeah.

00:09:01.707 --> 00:09:03.543
- And capable of anything.
- Yeah.

00:09:03.543 --> 00:09:05.002
- That's what got me on edge

00:09:05.002 --> 00:09:06.546
with it.
- I know.

00:09:06.546 --> 00:09:08.464
I really loved seeing you be a dad,

00:09:08.464 --> 00:09:09.382
"One Battle After Another,"

00:09:09.382 --> 00:09:12.385
I like, I'm so sad that you
don't have a teenage daughter,

00:09:12.385 --> 00:09:14.637
you look great with one.

00:09:14.637 --> 00:09:15.972
(Leonardo and Jennifer laughing)

00:09:15.972 --> 00:09:18.808
We changed a lot, in the book,

00:09:18.808 --> 00:09:22.937
you know, the child is
not well taken care of,

00:09:22.937 --> 00:09:25.481
and Rob and I are both parents

00:09:25.481 --> 00:09:27.233
and like Rob had like a newborn

00:09:27.233 --> 00:09:30.027
and we just like were not capable of,

00:09:30.027 --> 00:09:32.822
I think even playing characters like that.

00:09:32.822 --> 00:09:35.491
And it changed, and I think that ended up

00:09:35.491 --> 00:09:38.244
being for the better because postpartum,

00:09:38.244 --> 00:09:41.163
I think we've only been talking
about it really recently-

00:09:41.163 --> 00:09:42.290
- Right.
- And so

00:09:42.290 --> 00:09:43.457
when we do talk about it,

00:09:43.457 --> 00:09:46.502
the only understanding of it
like is like a very simplistic,

00:09:46.502 --> 00:09:47.962
like, you don't connect with your child

00:09:47.962 --> 00:09:49.672
and you don't like your child-
- Yeah. Right.

00:09:49.672 --> 00:09:52.550
- When really that's
like one version of it.

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.010
You know, another version of it is

00:09:54.010 --> 00:09:55.636
your marriage starts to erode.

00:09:55.636 --> 00:09:56.554
- Right.
- 'cause your dynamic

00:09:56.554 --> 00:09:57.763
is completely different.

00:09:58.598 --> 00:09:59.682
- We dealt with a lot of that

00:09:59.682 --> 00:10:01.767
with Teyana's character too in the movie.

00:10:01.767 --> 00:10:03.227
- Yeah.
- Which was kind of

00:10:03.227 --> 00:10:05.146
something I didn't, wasn't really,

00:10:05.146 --> 00:10:07.106
I guess it was kind of
hinted at in the script,

00:10:07.106 --> 00:10:10.860
but this idea of me loving
the baby more than her

00:10:10.860 --> 00:10:13.446
and her being jealous of the baby

00:10:13.446 --> 00:10:15.114
and then all these secret conversations,

00:10:15.114 --> 00:10:17.908
but it was just a little
blip in the movie.

00:10:17.908 --> 00:10:18.951
- Yeah.
- Whereas you explored it.

00:10:18.951 --> 00:10:22.496
- Well I can, I imagine
how much that would

00:10:22.496 --> 00:10:24.582
happen for her specifically

00:10:24.582 --> 00:10:26.876
because she was doing
something so important.

00:10:27.835 --> 00:10:29.378
And then when you have a baby,

00:10:29.378 --> 00:10:31.714
it's hard to not just feel like an animal.

00:10:31.714 --> 00:10:33.174
- Right.
- And you're just like,

00:10:33.174 --> 00:10:35.509
I'm a useless cow that just,

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:38.888
I used to have a life, I
used to do important things.

00:10:38.888 --> 00:10:40.473
- Right.
- And I mean for her-

00:10:40.473 --> 00:10:42.016
- Right.
- She was doing like-

00:10:42.016 --> 00:10:43.434
- And then she almost blames me

00:10:43.434 --> 00:10:44.727
for being the paternal one

00:10:44.727 --> 00:10:45.561
in a weird way.
- Yeah.

00:10:45.561 --> 00:10:46.979
Yeah.
- And you'll never understand

00:10:46.979 --> 00:10:47.813
what I-
- I get it,

00:10:47.813 --> 00:10:49.023
I'm on Tammy's side.

00:10:49.023 --> 00:10:50.691
(Leonardo and Jennifer giggling)

00:10:50.691 --> 00:10:52.193
- I'm curious about something-

00:10:52.193 --> 00:10:53.069
- I was gonna ask you a question but-

00:10:53.069 --> 00:10:54.654
- Our work aside.

00:10:54.654 --> 00:10:55.946
- Okay.

00:10:55.946 --> 00:10:57.990
- No, but I mean we're both,

00:10:57.990 --> 00:10:59.575
